What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 11397 records in the dataset with 81 features. Most variables are numeric, but the variables are ordered factor variables with the following levels.

What is the main features of interest in the dataset?

  • I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the borrower rate (interest rate) of loans in the dataset.

  • I'm interested in how borrower rate changed in each state in the past few years.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your features of interest?

  • I expect that the variable CreditGrade, Term, LenderYield, ProsperScore, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeowner, CurrentlyInGroup, CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper, DebtToIncomeRatio, LoanOriginationDate have effects on borrower rate.

  • The variable LoanOriginationDate, BorrowerState will help me solve the second problem.

Data Cleaning¶

In [10]:
loan_clean=loan_sub.copy()

Define¶

  • Change the data type of CreditGrade into ordinal category.
  • Change the data type of Term into nominal category.
  • Change the data type of ProsperScore into string and then change it into category.
  • Change the data type of LoanOriginationDate into datetime.

Code¶

In [11]:
# CreditGrade
ranking=["AA","A","B","C","D","E","HR","NC"]
creditgrade=pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True,categories=ranking)
loan_clean.CreditGrade=loan_clean.CreditGrade.astype(creditgrade)
# ProsperScore
loan_clean["ProsperScore"]=loan_clean["ProsperScore"].astype(str)
prosper=["11.0","10.0","9.0","8.0","7.0","6.0","5.0","4.0","3.0","2.0","1.0"]
prosperscore=pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True,categories=prosper)
loan_clean.ProsperScore=loan_clean.ProsperScore.astype(prosperscore)
In [12]:
loan_clean.Term=loan_clean.Term.astype("category")
loan_clean.EmploymentStatus=loan_clean.EmploymentStatus.astype("category")
loan_clean.LoanOriginationDate=pd.to_datetime(loan_clean.LoanOriginationDate)

The borrower rate and lender yield has a strong linear relationship, as well as credit score range lower and credit score range upper. There's a weak relationship between DebtToIncomeRatio to other numeric variables which suprised me. I think the higher debt to income ratio is, the weaker the borrower's ability to pay back the loan which cause a higher borrower rate and lower credit score, so I'll dig into it later. The strong linear relationship between credit score range lower and upper makes sense, I decided to calculate the average of upper bound and lower bound to replace these two variables.

In [34]:
loan_clean["creditscore_avg"]=(loan_clean.CreditScoreRangeUpper+loan_clean.CreditScoreRangeUpper)/2

It seems there is a negative linear relationship between the borrower rate and CreditScoreRangeUpper and CreditScoreRangeLower (creditscore_avg). I decided to plot a heatmap to check.

From the above plots, we can see:
1. When credit grade going down, the credit score goes down as well, and then the borrower rate increases.
2. The longer the term is, the higher the borrower rate is on median level.
3. The lower the prosper score is, the higher the borrower rate is, there's a roughly positive linear relationship between prosper score and credit score. It make sense, prosper rate are calculated for those borrowers who have credit scores between 640 and 710.
4. Borrowers who are employed have lower borrower rate than those who are not employed. Full-time employed borrowers have lower borrower rate than those who are part-time employed, retire, or self-employed on median level. It make sense, people having a long-term job have long term cash flows to pay back the loans. People who have long term jobs have higher credit score upper bound.
5. Homeowners seem to have higher credit grade and lower borrower rate.
6. The borrower rate has fluctuated in the past few years, but the credit score has increased since 2006 to 2009 and kept stable at a certain level after 2009.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I noticed homeowners usually have lower credit score and higher borrower rate. And borrowers who are employed or full-time employed are mostly having high credit score and low borrower rate, especially for full-time employed borrowers. Except that, I also noticed that the slope of the average credit score and borrower rate is getting more and more steeper as the year went by, meaning the borrower rate is getting more and more sensitive to the change of credit score. Finally, I noticed the plot is less spread when the term is longer. In my opinion, this is because longterm interest rate is more stable than short term interest rate.
